[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Considering writing a fiction book related to women going through perimenopause and menopause symptoms.And I want to and it'll be a little bit of a comedy slash drama.But something that would have maybe a series and could turn into a youtube series or a television show by the way, I want to do some research on what other books do have.The central focus about perimenopause and menopause.Are there any amazon books or things in the public domain that are not medical books or people talking it from a health perspective?But true fiction books related to the scenario, put as much detailed information as you can put into a detailed table with the author the title of the book.What the book is about the year it was published.And if there's an accurate working amazon link to the book 22 Must-Read Books About Menopause, Perimenopause https://www.theflowspace.com/lists/menopause-perimenopause-books/ All the rage: the rise of the menopause novel | Fiction | The Guardian https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/jun/03/all-the-rage-the-rise-of-the-menopause-novel 09 - A book that features a character going through menopause ... https://www.goodreads.com/topic/show/22960083-09---a-book-that-features-a-character-going-through-menopause 44 sources Mixture-of-Agents gpt-5 Claude Sonnet 4 Gemini 2.5 Flash Reflection The responses provided by different models cover a broad spectrum of fictional books dealing with perimenopause and menopause. Here's a detailed reflection on each model's output: 1. **Gemini-2.5-Flash**: This model has summarized multiple books, detailing the author, title, and general overview of each book's content focusing on perimenopause and menopause. It emphasizes comedic and dramatic elements while providing Amazon links. The content is comprehensive and well-structured, detailing publication years, authors, and synopses. However, it occasionally repeats information and lacks deeper exploration into how each book uniquely addresses menopause. 2. **Claude-Sonnet-4**: This model offers detailed descriptions of books, encompassing comedic elements in perimenopause fiction. It also highlights an emerging subgenre, \"peri-fiction,\" and examines its impact on literature. Strengths include recognition of broader literary movements and contextualization of themes in the books. Its weakness lies in insufficient focus on individual books. 3. **GPT-5**: This response is more structured around contemporary fiction focused on perimenopause, combining humor and drama. It provides numerous details such as authors, synopsis, and availability. Several books are explored in depth, but much of the information appears repetitious across different entries. The model offers insight into how menopause influences narrative themes, though less focus is on specific narrative insights. The search results reveal various fictional novels addressing both perimenopause and menopause, focusing more on thematic explorations rather than medical advice. They include unique narratives that examine menopausal experiences through a blend of comedic and dramatic lenses, reflecting societal attitudes toward aging women, personal transformation, and empowerment[2](https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/jun/03/all-the-rage-the-rise-of-the-menopause-novel \"theguardian.com\")[3](https://www.goodreads.com/topic/show/22960083-09---a-book-that-features-a-character-going-through-menopause \"goodreads.com\")[5](https://capsulenz.com/covet/putting-the-hot-into-hot-mess-the-rise-of-the-chaotic-cathartic-perimenopausal-novel/ \"capsulenz.com\"). Fictional Books on Perimenopause and Menopause Fictional books offer a blend of comedy and drama while focusing on women experiencing perimenopause and menopause. These narratives provide insights into midlife transitions without medical perspectives. All Fours Author: Miranda July Synopsis: This novel is described as chaotic, sexually explicit, and laugh-out-loud funny, exploring the narrator's journey through perimenopause and menopause520. It blends comedy with tender exploration, making it a staple in the rising genre of menopause novels. Publication Year: 2024 Sandwich Author: Catherine Newman Synopsis: During a chaotic family vacation, a mother juggles hot flashes, caretaking, adult children, and marriage, with humor and heartache8. Publication Year: 2023 Amazing Grace Adams Author: Fran Littlewood Synopsis: This debut novel follows a woman experiencing perimenopause as she goes on a rampage across London, blending humor with the emotional challenges of perimenopause2. Publication Year: 2023 Woman of a Certain Rage Author: Georgie Hall Synopsis: Eliza navigates family and work life amid menopausal symptoms in this smart, funny dramedy about reinvention6. Publication Year: 2021 Hot Not Bothered Author: Harper Ford Synopsis: This romantic comedy presents menopause with humor and woe, offering a new perspective on traditional romcoms7. Publication Year: 2024 The Change Author: Kirsten Miller Synopsis: As a magical realist thriller, this novel follows three women who discover special powers during menopause, embracing empowerment and humor40. Publication Year: 2022 These novels delve into midlife transition, showcasing comedy and drama while portraying women's experiences with menopause, allowing readers to explore the narratives of resilience and transformation.12356 What are the themes explored in menopause novels? How do fictional novels portray menopause differently from nonfiction? What role does humor play in novels about menopause? Put the top fifteen books related to the perimenopause and menopause scenario in a detailed table format and the live link to the amazon product page for the book 09 - A book that features a character going through menopause ... https://www.goodreads.com/topic/show/22960083-09---a-book-that-features-a-character-going-through-menopause 22 Must-Read Books About Menopause, Perimenopause https://www.theflowspace.com/lists/menopause-perimenopause-books/ All the rage: the rise of the menopause novel | Fiction | The Guardian https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/jun/03/all-the-rage-the-rise-of-the-menopause-novel 19 sources Top Fifteen Fictional Comedy-Drama Books on Perimenopause and Menopause Scenarios The following table lists fifteen fictional books in comedy-drama style that explore perimenopause and menopause themes through humorous yet dramatic narratives. These selections focus on character-driven stories of midlife transitions, family dynamics, and personal growth, drawing from popular recommendations and lists. Selections prioritize books with elements of wit, satire, and emotional depth while excluding purely medical or health-focused non-fiction. Each entry includes the author, title, a brief synopsis, publication year, and a direct Amazon product page link for reference13711. Author\tTitle\tSynopsis\tPublication Year\tAmazon Link Miranda July\tAll Fours\tA semi-autobiographical tale of a 45-year-old artist who embarks on a chaotic cross-country road trip, only to hole up in a motel for a transformative affair, exploring perimenopausal desires, identity shifts, and marital reinvention with sharp humor and introspection.\t2024\thttps://www.amazon.com/All-Fours-Novel-Miranda-July/dp/0593190262 Catherine Newman\tSandwich\tA middle-aged woman navigates a family vacation with her grown children and aging parents, confronting perimenopausal symptoms like hot flashes amid comedic family chaos, reflections on motherhood, and unexpected revelations.\t2024\thttps://www.amazon.com/Sandwich-Novel-Catherine-Newman/dp/0063345161 Marian Keyes\tMy Favourite Mistake\tAnna Walsh, a 48-year-old woman dealing with perimenopause, returns to Ireland from New York, facing old flames, new jobs, and hormonal upheavals in a witty story of reinvention and romance.\t2024\thttps://www.amazon.com/My-Favourite-Mistake-Marian-Keyes/dp/0385695403 Fran Littlewood\tAmazing Grace Adams\tA 45-year-old woman rampages through London on a hot day to deliver a birthday cake to her estranged daughter, flashing back to her perimenopausal struggles, marital breakdown, and fierce reclaiming of self in a blend of rage and humor.\t2023\thttps://www.amazon.com/Amazing-Grace-Adams-Fran-Littlewood/dp/1250857015 Kirsten Miller\tThe Change\tThree midlife women discover supernatural powers during menopause, teaming up to solve a murder in a magical realist thriller infused with comedy about empowerment, hot flashes, and defying societal expectations.\t2022\thttps://www.amazon.com/Change-Novel-Kirsten-Miller/dp/0063144042 Joanne Harris\tBroken Light\tA menopausal woman gains the ability to enter others' minds, using it to confront predatory men and her own past in a darkly humorous revenge fantasy inspired by Stephen King's Carrie.\t2023\thttps://www.amazon.com/Broken-Light-Joanne-Harris/dp/1639364714 Fannie Flagg\tFried Green Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop Cafe\tAn elderly woman recounts tales of friendship and life in a small town, touching on menopause and aging through comedic and heartfelt stories of resilience and community.\t1987\thttps://www.amazon.com/Fried-Green-Tomatoes-Whistle-Stop/dp/0449911357 Nancy Thayer\tThe Hot Flash Club\tFour women in their fifties form a club to tackle menopause symptoms, embark on adventures, and support each other through humorous escapades and life changes.\t2003\thttps://www.amazon.com/Hot-Flash-Club-Nancy-Thayer/dp/0345468627 Georgie Hall\tWoman of a Certain Rage\tA 50-something woman navigates family life, career, and perimenopausal rage with wit, exploring relationships and self-discovery in a warm, engaging narrative.\t2021\thttps://www.amazon.com/Woman-Certain-Rage-Georgie-Hall/dp/1800249527 Jeanne Ray\tCalling Invisible Women\tA middle-aged woman literally becomes invisible during menopause, using it to her advantage in comedic adventures while addressing themes of being overlooked in society.\t2012\thttps://www.amazon.com/Calling-Invisible-Women-Novel-Jeanne/dp/0307395065 Nancy Peach\tHot Mother\tA menopausal mother deals with family chaos, hormonal shifts, and unexpected twists in a hilarious take on midlife motherhood and personal reinvention.\t2024\thttps://www.amazon.com/Hot-Mother-Nancy-Peach/dp/1916753043 Stevie Turner\tNo Sex Please, I'm Menopausal!\tA woman faces libido loss and marital strain during menopause, leading to comedic and dramatic explorations of relationships and self-worth.\t2014\thttps://www.amazon.com/No-Sex-Please-Im-Menopausal/dp/1505216400 Allison Pearson\tHow Hard Can It Be?\tKate Reddy juggles career, family, and perimenopause in a satirical sequel, highlighting the absurdities of midlife with sharp humor and emotional depth.\t2017\thttps://www.amazon.com/How-Hard-Can-Be-Allison-Pearson/dp/1250086086 Dana Spiotta\tWayward\tA woman in her fifties buys a rundown house amid perimenopausal turmoil and political unrest, reflecting on aging, motherhood, and rebellion with wry comedy.\t2021\thttps://www.amazon.com/Wayward-Novel-Dana-Spiotta/dp/0593318730 Jane Roper\tThe Society of Shame\tA politician's wife becomes a viral sensation due to a menopausal mishap, leading to satirical fame and self-empowerment in a comedic critique of social media.\t2023\thttps://www.amazon.com/Society-Shame-Jane-Roper/dp/0593468767 Several additional titles emerged from further exploration of reader discussions and literary analyses, expanding the selection with more comedy-drama narratives centered on perimenopausal and menopausal experiences. These include horror-infused comedies and magical realist tales that blend humor with emotional depth, often highlighting themes of empowerment and societal invisibility. For instance, Mary by Nat Cassidy features a middle-aged woman confronting terrifying visions and bodily changes during menopause, reimagining Stephen King's Carrie in a darkly comedic horror framework13. Another noteworthy addition is The New Moon's Arms by Nalo Hopkinson, where a grandmother in her 50s navigates menopause while rediscovering childhood magical powers, weaving comedy with reflections on aging and family in a Caribbean setting1. Beatrix and Fred by Emily Spurr offers an off-kilter love story between two older characters dealing with loneliness and menopause, wrapped in moral complexity and sheer fun6. The Wife Who Got a Life by Tracy Bloom follows a woman's humorous journey through midlife reinvention, tackling perimenopausal challenges with smart, joyous celebration8. These enrich the genre by introducing diverse cultural perspectives and supernatural elements, complementing the character-driven focus on midlife transitions. To incorporate these, here's an updated table with four new entries replacing less central ones from the original list, ensuring the top 15 remain focused on comedy-drama style while prioritizing highly recommended works from community lists and critiques134678. Author\tTitle\tSynopsis\tPublication Year\tAmazon Link Nat Cassidy\tMary: An Awakening of Terror\tA quiet middle-aged woman returns to her hometown amid menopausal hot flashes and visions of a serial killer, blending horror-comedy with themes of self-discovery and inner turmoil in a nod to Carrie.\t2022\thttps://www.amazon.com/Mary-Awakening-Terror-Nat-Cassidy/dp/1250265231 Nalo Hopkinson\tThe New Moon's Arms\tA 50-something grandmother experiences menopause alongside the return of her childhood magic, leading to comedic and poignant adventures involving lost children and personal rebirth.\t2007\thttps://www.amazon.com/New-Moons-Arms-Nalo-Hopkinson/dp/0446576913 Emily Spurr\tBeatrix and Fred\tAn unconventional romance between two aging protagonists navigating menopause, loneliness, and unexpected connections, delivered with warmth, humor, and moral depth.\t2023\thttps://www.amazon.com/Beatrix-Fred-Emily-Spurr/dp/1922790400 Tracy Bloom\tThe Wife Who Got a Life\tA perimenopausal woman embarks on a year of bold challenges to reclaim her life, filled with laugh-out-loud moments amid family and hormonal chaos.\t2021\thttps://www.amazon.com/Wife-Who-Got-Life/dp/000843428X This answer isn't good enough? Try Mixture-of-Agents What are reader reviews and ratings for the top comedy-drama books on menopause? How do cultural differences influence menopause portrayals in international fiction? Are there any upcoming 2025 releases in menopause-themed comedy-drama novels? Mixture-of-Agents Search Web"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Source: "},{"type":"link","href":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=1328fd9c-66b3-45cf-aafb-61270f7ebb98","children":[{"text":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=1328fd9c-66b3-45cf-aafb-61270f7ebb98"}]}]}]
